1
00:00:01,120 --> 00:00:05,410
The volume weighted average price (VWAP) is
a trading benchmark used by traders that gives

2
00:00:05,410 --> 00:00:10,600
the average price a stock has traded throughout
the day, based on both volume and price.

3
00:00:10,600 --> 00:00:15,260
It is important because it provides traders
with insight into both the trend and value

4
00:00:15,260 --> 00:00:16,840
of a security.

5
00:00:16,840 --> 00:00:19,840
The Formula for the Volume Weighted Average
Price (VWAP) is pretty simple.

6
00:00:19,840 --> 00:00:24,730
You add up the dollars traded for every transaction
(so, the price multiplied by the number of

7
00:00:24,730 --> 00:00:29,450
shares traded) and then divide by the total
shares traded.

8
00:00:29,450 --> 00:00:33,130
On a chart, VWAP and a moving average may
look similar.

9
00:00:33,130 --> 00:00:36,350
These two indicators are calculating different
things.

10
00:00:36,350 --> 00:00:42,660
VWAP is calculating the sum of price multiplied
by volume, divided by total volume, while

11
00:00:42,660 --> 00:00:48,329
a simple moving average is calculated by summing
up closing prices over a certain period (say

12
00:00:48,329 --> 00:00:52,370
20), and then dividing it by how many periods
there are (20).

13
00:00:52,370 --> 00:00:55,609
Volume is not factored in.

14
00:00:55,609 --> 00:01:00,179
The volume weighted average price (VWAP) appears
as a single line on intraday charts (1 minute,

15
00:01:00,179 --> 00:01:03,329
15 minute, and so on), similar to how a moving
average looks.

16
00:01:03,329 --> 00:01:09,890
Like moving averages, VWAP lags price because
it is an average based on past data.

17
00:01:09,890 --> 00:01:14,470
Despite this lag, you can compare VWAP with
the current price to determine the general

18
00:01:14,470 --> 00:01:17,000
direction of intraday prices.

19
00:01:17,000 --> 00:01:19,340
It works similar to a moving average.

20
00:01:19,340 --> 00:01:24,570
In general, intraday prices are falling when
below VWAP and intraday prices are rising

21
00:01:24,570 --> 00:01:26,550
when above VWAP.

22
00:01:26,550 --> 00:01:31,960
So A rising VWAP, with the price above the
VWAP line, means the price is likely in an

23
00:01:31,960 --> 00:01:33,100
short term uptrend.

24
00:01:33,100 --> 00:01:39,000
A declining VWAP, with the price below the
VWAP line, means the price is likely in a

25
00:01:39,000 --> 00:01:40,830
short term downtrend.

26
00:01:40,830 --> 00:01:47,930
Also, don't rely on VWAP exclusively to determine
trend, since it is only showing a historical

27
00:01:47,930 --> 00:01:54,490
average, and not what is happening currently
or in the future.

28
00:01:54,490 --> 00:01:57,520
What Does Volume Weighted Average Price (VWAP)
Tell You?

29
00:01:57,520 --> 00:02:02,470
Large institutional buyers and mutual funds
use the VWAP indicator to move into or out

30
00:02:02,470 --> 00:02:05,970
of stocks with a market impact as small as
possible.

31
00:02:05,970 --> 00:02:09,640
They use VWAP to identify liquidity points.

32
00:02:09,640 --> 00:02:14,819
The idea is not to disrupt the market when
entering large buy or sell orders.

33
00:02:14,819 --> 00:02:21,040
VWAP helps these institutions determine the
liquid and illiquid price points for a specific

34
00:02:21,040 --> 00:02:23,900
security over a very short time period.

35
00:02:23,900 --> 00:02:30,170
Therefore, when possible, institutions will
try to buy below the VWAP, or sell above it.

36
00:02:30,170 --> 00:02:36,079
This way their actions push the price back
toward the average, instead of away from it.

37
00:02:36,079 --> 00:02:40,030
VWAP can also be used to measure trading efficiency.

38
00:02:40,030 --> 00:02:46,099
After buying or selling a stock, big market
players can compare their price to VWAP values.

39
00:02:46,099 --> 00:02:51,459
A buy order executed below the VWAP value
would be considered a good fill because the

40
00:02:51,459 --> 00:02:54,379
security was bought at a below average price.

41
00:02:54,379 --> 00:03:00,650
Conversely, a sell order executed above the
VWAP would be considered a good fill because

42
00:03:00,650 --> 00:03:05,459
it was sold at an above average price.

43
00:03:05,459 --> 00:03:10,549
Retail traders, on the other hand, tend to
use VWAP more as a trend confirmation tool,

44
00:03:10,549 --> 00:03:11,659
similar to a moving average.

45
00:03:11,659 --> 00:03:16,540
When the price is above VWAP they look only
to initiate long positions.

46
00:03:16,540 --> 00:03:21,099
When the price is below VWAP they only look
to initiate short positions.

47
00:03:21,099 --> 00:03:26,780
This is why day traders love the VWAP indicator,
because more than often, the price finds support

48
00:03:26,780 --> 00:03:29,150
and resistance around the VWAP.

49
00:03:29,150 --> 00:03:33,439
Knowing that other traders and algorithms
are buying and selling around the VWAP line,

50
00:03:33,439 --> 00:03:36,239
if you combine the VWAP with simple price
action, a VWAP strategy can help you find

51
00:03:36,239 --> 00:03:39,049
dynamic support and resistance levels in the
market.

52
00:03:39,049 --> 00:03:44,510
Also, the likelihood of a VWAP line becoming
a dynamic support and resistance zone becomes

53
00:03:44,510 --> 00:03:46,590
higher when the market is trending.

54
00:03:46,590 --> 00:03:52,049
So, for uptrends for example, look for higher
highs and highs lows and pay attention at

55
00:03:52,049 --> 00:03:54,700
the price action around the VWAP.

56
00:03:54,700 --> 00:04:00,169
Here are a few reasons why so many top day
traders love VWAP:

57
00:04:00,169 --> 00:04:05,379
VWAP is a simple indicator: the price is either
above it or below it.

58
00:04:05,379 --> 00:04:09,349
When it comes to day trading, simplicity often
rules.

59
00:04:09,349 --> 00:04:15,849
It’s an easy measurement on whether a stock
is cheap or expensive on the day.

60
00:04:15,849 --> 00:04:21,519
You can use it to help you pinpoint intelligent
entry and exit points for your day trades.

61
00:04:21,519 --> 00:04:27,410
It can help you determine trend changes, often
quicker than moving averages.

62
00:04:27,410 --> 00:04:31,190
Now, how to trade with the VWAP?

63
00:04:31,190 --> 00:04:36,139
You can use it for 2 types of trades: breakouts
and pullbacks.

64
00:04:36,139 --> 00:04:40,740
VWAP breakout setup is very simple but not
what you may be thinking.

65
00:04:40,740 --> 00:04:45,550
So a bullish breakout is when a stock’s
price moves above a previously strongly held

66
00:04:45,550 --> 00:04:48,990
resistance level, often with higher trading
volume.

67
00:04:48,990 --> 00:04:54,050
This can signal that traders are excited about
this move and the stock may go on an extended

68
00:04:54,050 --> 00:04:55,460
price run.

69
00:04:55,460 --> 00:05:01,170
But we are not looking for a breakout to new
highs but a break above the VWAP itself with

70
00:05:01,170 --> 00:05:02,170
strength.

71
00:05:02,170 --> 00:05:06,479
When it comes to a VWAP breakout, we look
for periods when a stock price drops below

72
00:05:06,479 --> 00:05:08,069
the VWAP.

73
00:05:08,069 --> 00:05:13,039
This can often signal that buyers are exiting
their long positions, which lowers the price

74
00:05:13,039 --> 00:05:15,509
compared to the VWAP.

75
00:05:15,509 --> 00:05:20,069
This can potentially be a good situation to
look for a long trade, with the expectation

76
00:05:20,069 --> 00:05:24,550
that the stock will soon bounce back and continue
its upward movement.

77
00:05:24,550 --> 00:05:29,169
Essentially, you wait for the stock to test
the VWAP to the downside.

78
00:05:29,169 --> 00:05:34,610
Next, you will want to look for the stock
to close above the VWAP.

79
00:05:34,610 --> 00:05:39,110
You will then look to buy above the high of
the candle that closed above the VWAP.

80
00:05:39,110 --> 00:06:04,169
Here are some examples of VWAP breakout trades.

81
00:06:04,169 --> 00:06:06,430
Next is the VWAP Pullback trade.

82
00:06:06,430 --> 00:06:11,289
A pullback is where a stock that’s on an
extended move upward or downward makes a small

83
00:06:11,289 --> 00:06:13,860
movement in the opposite direction.

84
00:06:13,860 --> 00:06:17,470
Pullbacks are a common price movement, especially
in heavy trends.

85
00:06:17,470 --> 00:06:23,409
To trade a VWAP pullback setup, you have to
find a stock that’s in a clear uptrend,

86
00:06:23,409 --> 00:06:26,490
consistently making higher highs and higher
lows.

87
00:06:26,490 --> 00:06:32,229
The stock price makes a pullback to the downside,
returning to the VWAP level on the chart.

88
00:06:32,229 --> 00:06:37,080
This is a chance to buy the stock at the daily
average price.

89
00:06:37,080 --> 00:06:42,100
After you enter your long, you’re looking
for price to continue its uptrend, gradually

90
00:06:42,100 --> 00:06:45,800
pulling the VWAP up along with it.

91
00:06:45,800 --> 00:06:55,780
Here are some examples of VWAP pullback trades.

92
00:06:55,780 --> 00:07:16,020
Here’s an important tip: If you use longer-term
charts, such as the 30-minute or 60-minute,

93
00:07:16,020 --> 00:07:22,650
your VWAP data will greatly lag behind a shorter-term
chart (like the 1-minute or 5-minute).

94
00:07:22,650 --> 00:07:28,310
On a longer-term chart, the speed at which
the VWAP generates a signal could mean that

95
00:07:28,310 --> 00:07:30,060
you completely miss the move.

96
00:07:30,060 --> 00:07:34,180
So, if you use VWAP, opt for the shorter-term
charts.

97
00:07:34,180 --> 00:07:38,530
Also, you have to be smart with where you
place your stop-loss.

98
00:07:38,530 --> 00:07:44,219
A common mistake is to place your stops few
points below the VWAP.

99
00:07:44,219 --> 00:07:48,699
You will be stopped out often of you place
your stops close to the VWAP.

100
00:07:48,699 --> 00:07:50,740
There’s a smarter way.

101
00:07:50,740 --> 00:07:55,960
For instance, if you take a VWAP pullback
trade, you should look to place your stop-loss

102
00:07:55,960 --> 00:07:58,720
on the other side of a key chart level.

103
00:07:58,720 --> 00:08:03,349
That level may be below a pivot point or previous
strong support level.

104
00:08:03,349 --> 00:08:08,979
That way, you can use the VWAP to try to keep
trading in the right direction but maintain

105
00:08:08,979 --> 00:08:11,660
a stop-loss at a logical level.

106
00:08:11,660 --> 00:08:17,449
Alternatively, if there’s no major level,
you can also look to keep your stock on the

107
00:08:17,449 --> 00:08:20,160
other side of a recent swing point.

108
00:08:20,160 --> 00:08:24,610
So if you’re long a stock that’s making
higher highs and higher lows, you can place

109
00:08:24,610 --> 00:08:29,760
your stop-loss just below the previous swing
low.

110
00:08:29,760 --> 00:08:32,909
The VWAP itself is a simple and effective
indicator.

111
00:08:32,909 --> 00:08:38,610
But that doesn’t mean you can just plug
and play, then expect killer result.

112
00:08:38,610 --> 00:08:42,289
The Volume Weighted Average Price (VWAP) has
its limitations.

113
00:08:42,289 --> 00:08:48,680
VWAP is considered a single-day indicator,
and is restarted at the open of each new trading

114
00:08:48,680 --> 00:08:49,839
day.

115
00:08:49,839 --> 00:08:55,149
Attempting to create an average VWAP over
many days could mean that the average becomes

116
00:08:55,149 --> 00:08:57,690
distorted from the true VWAP reading.

117
00:08:57,690 --> 00:09:03,589
Also, don’t forget that VWAP is based on
historical values and does not have predictive

118
00:09:03,589 --> 00:09:04,639
qualities.

119
00:09:04,639 --> 00:09:08,820
VWAP serves as a reference point for prices
for one day.

120
00:09:08,820 --> 00:09:13,649
For this reason, it is best suited for intraday
analysis.

121
00:09:13,649 --> 00:09:19,930
Keep in mind that VWAP is a cumulative indicator,
which means the number of data points progressively

122
00:09:19,930 --> 00:09:25,690
increases throughout the day.

123
00:09:25,690 --> 00:09:31,630
This is why VWAP lags price and this lag increases
as the day extends.

124
00:09:31,630 --> 00:09:36,779
Once you apply the VWAP to your day trading
setup, you will soon realize that it is like

125
00:09:36,779 --> 00:09:38,100
any other indicator.

126
00:09:38,100 --> 00:09:44,250
There are some stocks and markets where it
will pinpoint entries just right and in others

127
00:09:44,250 --> 00:09:45,710
it will appear worthless.

128
00:09:45,710 --> 00:09:51,310
That’s why, I encourage you to use the VWAP
indicator in combination with price action,

129
00:09:51,310 --> 00:09:55,870
so you can simplify your decision-making process
and make better trades.

130
00:09:55,870 --> 00:10:00,279
As always, if you learned something new, make
sure you subscribe, click the bell icon to

131
00:10:00,279 --> 00:10:03,450
enable notifications and leave us a like to
show your support.

132
00:10:03,450 --> 00:10:04,650
